## Set up Cloudinary in Next.js

### 1. Create a Cloudinary account
- Sign up at https://cloudinary.com (free tier includes 25GB storage and 25GB monthly bandwidth).
- From the dashboard, copy your **Cloud Name**, **API Key**, and **API Secret**.

### 2. Install next-cloudinary
- Install the Next.js-specific Cloudinary package:
  ```
  npm install next-cloudinary
  ```
- `next-cloudinary` is the official Next.js integration. Do NOT use the generic `cloudinary` npm package alone for image rendering — it doesn't integrate with Next.js Image optimization.

### 3. Configure environment variables
- Add to `.env.local`:
  ```
  NEXT_PUBLIC_CLOUDINARY_CLOUD_NAME=your-cloud-name
  CLOUDINARY_API_KEY=your-api-key
  CLOUDINARY_API_SECRET=your-api-secret
  ```
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_CLOUDINARY_CLOUD_NAME` must be prefixed with `NEXT_PUBLIC_` — it is used client-side by `CldImage` and `CldUploadWidget`.
- `CLOUDINARY_API_KEY` and `CLOUDINARY_API_SECRET` must NOT be `NEXT_PUBLIC_` — they are used server-side only.
- NEVER expose `CLOUDINARY_API_SECRET` to the client. This allows destructive operations on your account.

### 4. Update `next.config.ts`
- Allow Cloudinary's image domains:
  ```ts
  import type { NextConfig } from 'next';
  const nextConfig: NextConfig = {
    images: {
      remotePatterns: [
        { protocol: 'https', hostname: 'res.cloudinary.com' },
      ],
    },
  };
  export default nextConfig;
  ```
- This is required for `next/image` to load Cloudinary URLs. Without it, Next.js will block external image sources.

### 5. Display images with CldImage
- Replace `next/image` with `CldImage` for Cloudinary-hosted assets:
  ```tsx
  import { CldImage } from 'next-cloudinary';

  export function ProductImage({ publicId }: { publicId: string }) {
    return (
      <CldImage
        src={publicId}
        width={800}
        height={600}
        alt="Product image"
        crop="fill"
        gravity="auto"
      />
    );
  }
  ```
- `src` is the Cloudinary **public ID** (e.g. `products/shirt-blue`), not a full URL.
- `CldImage` automatically selects WebP or AVIF based on browser support.
- `crop="fill"` + `gravity="auto"` uses Cloudinary's AI to smart-crop around the main subject.

### 6. Common transformations
- **Resize and crop:**
  ```tsx
  <CldImage src="my-image" width={400} height={400} crop="fill" gravity="face" alt="Portrait" />
  ```
- **Background removal (AI):**
  ```tsx
  <CldImage src="my-image" width={400} height={400} removeBackground alt="No background" />
  ```
- **Overlay text:**
  ```tsx
  <CldImage
    src="my-image"
    width={800}
    height={400}
    overlays={[{ text: { color: 'white', fontSize: 48, text: 'Hello World' }, position: { gravity: 'south', y: 20 } }]}
    alt="Image with text"
  />
  ```
- **Round corners:**
  ```tsx
  <CldImage src="my-image" width={200} height={200} crop="fill" roundCorners={50} alt="Rounded" />
  ```

### 7. Upload images from the client with CldUploadWidget
- Use the Cloudinary Upload Widget for drag-and-drop or click-to-upload:
  ```tsx
  'use client';
  import { CldUploadWidget } from 'next-cloudinary';

  export function ImageUploader({ onUpload }: { onUpload: (publicId: string) => void }) {
    return (
      <CldUploadWidget
        uploadPreset="your-upload-preset"
        onSuccess={(result) => {
          if (result.event === 'success') {
            const info = result.info as { public_id: string };
            onUpload(info.public_id);
          }
        }}
      >
        {({ open }) => (
          <button onClick={() => open()} type="button">
            Upload Image
          </button>
        )}
      </CldUploadWidget>
    );
  }
  ```
- Create an **Upload Preset** in the Cloudinary dashboard under Settings > Upload:
  - Set to **unsigned** for client-side uploads (simpler but less control).
  - Set to **signed** for server-controlled uploads (recommended for production).
- The `public_id` returned in `result.info` is what you save to your database.

### 8. Signed uploads (production-recommended)
- For signed uploads, create an API route to generate signatures:
  ```ts
  // src/app/api/cloudinary-signature/route.ts
  import { v2 as cloudinary } from 'cloudinary';
  import { NextResponse } from 'next/server';

  cloudinary.config({
    api_key: process.env.CLOUDINARY_API_KEY!,
    api_secret: process.env.CLOUDINARY_API_SECRET!,
    cloud_name: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_CLOUDINARY_CLOUD_NAME!,
  });

  export async function GET() {
    const timestamp = Math.round(new Date().getTime() / 1000);
    const signature = cloudinary.utils.api_sign_request(
      { timestamp, folder: 'uploads' },
      process.env.CLOUDINARY_API_SECRET!
    );
    return NextResponse.json({ timestamp, signature, api_key: process.env.CLOUDINARY_API_KEY });
  }
  ```
- Install the full SDK for server operations: `npm install cloudinary`.
- Pass `signatureEndpoint="/api/cloudinary-signature"` to `CldUploadWidget`.

### 9. Server-side operations (delete, rename, list)
- Use the `cloudinary` package server-side:
  ```ts
  import { v2 as cloudinary } from 'cloudinary';

  cloudinary.config({
    cloud_name: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_CLOUDINARY_CLOUD_NAME,
    api_key: process.env.CLOUDINARY_API_KEY,
    api_secret: process.env.CLOUDINARY_API_SECRET,
  });

  // Delete an asset
  await cloudinary.uploader.destroy('products/shirt-blue');

  // Upload from server (e.g. from a URL or buffer)
  const result = await cloudinary.uploader.upload('https://example.com/image.jpg', {
    folder: 'products',
    public_id: 'shirt-blue',
  });
  ```
- Always call server-side Cloudinary operations from Server Actions or API Routes — never from Client Components.

### 10. Video delivery with CldVideoPlayer
- Display Cloudinary-hosted videos:
  ```tsx
  import { CldVideoPlayer } from 'next-cloudinary';
  import 'next-cloudinary/dist/cld-video-player.css';

  export function ProductVideo({ publicId }: { publicId: string }) {
    return (
      <CldVideoPlayer
        src={publicId}
        width={1920}
        height={1080}
        autoPlay
        muted
      />
    );
  }
  ```
- Cloudinary automatically serves the optimal video format (WebM, MP4) and bitrate per device.

### Common errors & fixes
- **`Invalid src prop on next/image`** → You are using `next/image` with a Cloudinary URL. Switch to `CldImage` or add `res.cloudinary.com` to `remotePatterns` in `next.config.ts`.
- **`NEXT_PUBLIC_CLOUDINARY_CLOUD_NAME is undefined`** → Missing env var or forgot the `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix. Restart the dev server after adding `.env.local`.
- **`Upload Widget not opening`** → `uploadPreset` is required. Create one in the Cloudinary dashboard first.
- **`Unauthorized` on signed uploads** → API Secret is wrong or the signature endpoint returned an error. Check server logs.
- **Images not transforming** → You are passing a full URL as `src` instead of a public ID. Use only the public ID (e.g. `products/shirt-blue`).
- **`Error: Must supply api_secret`** → You called a server-side Cloudinary function without configuring `cloudinary.config()`. Call it before any API operations.
- **Large images loading slowly** → Ensure `width` and `height` props match your display size. Cloudinary serves the wrong dimensions if they don't match the layout.
- **Background removal not working** → The AI background removal feature requires a paid plan or add-on. Check your Cloudinary plan.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT expose `CLOUDINARY_API_SECRET` with the `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix — anyone can then delete or upload to your account.
- Do NOT store full Cloudinary URLs in your database — store only the `public_id`. URLs can change if you migrate regions or cloud names.
- Do NOT use unsigned upload presets in production without folder restrictions — anyone can upload to your account. Use signed uploads or restrict the preset to a specific folder.
- Do NOT skip `next.config.ts` `remotePatterns` — images will fail to load in production even if they work in dev.
- Do NOT pass a full URL as `src` to `CldImage` — it expects a Cloudinary public ID, not a URL.
- Do NOT call `cloudinary.uploader` or `cloudinary.api` from Client Components — these require the API secret which must stay server-side.
- Do NOT omit `alt` on `CldImage` — it is required for accessibility and Next.js will warn.
- Do NOT use the generic `cloudinary` npm package for image rendering in Next.js — use `next-cloudinary` which integrates with the Image component pipeline.
